instruction: [INST] Analyze this file to learn MacBook motherboard repair. The 'definitions' section explains key technical terms. The 'threads' section contains real-world repair discussions. Use both sections to understand and learn how to troubleshoot MacBook issues. Posts from username 'larossmann' , 'dukefawks' , and '2informaticos' are posts from trusted experts.[/INST]

definitions.A1466: What is A1466? A1466 is a model number for a 13 inch size MacBook Air from years Early 2015, 2017, Mid 2012, Mid 2013, Early 2014 with EMC 2925, that may contain one of these boards depending on the year & configuration: 820-00165, 820-3209, 820-3437..
definitions.820-3437: What is 820-3437? a LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER.
definitions.C1950: What is C1950? Capacitor between PP3V42_G3H & ground on pin 8 of U1950 on 2013-2015 Macbook Pros & Airs that often corrodes. When corroded, pin 8 on U1950 will be damaged, which will prevent machine from booting and cause PM_SLP_S4_L to pulse. .
definitions.3V3_S5: What is 3V3_S5? 3V3_S5 and PP3V3_S5 are interchangeable, see definition for PP3V3_S5. .
definitions.PP3V3_SUS: What is PP3V3_SUS? The "PP3V3_SUS" rail on a MacBook logic board is a power rail that provides a 3.3-volt supply to the suspend-to-RAM (S3 state) components. .
definitions.U1950: What is U1950? This chip often becomes corroded on pin 8 on the PP3V42_G3H pin causing PM_SLP_S4_L to go missing.

threads.title: <MACBOOK MODEL NUMBER>A1466</MACBOOK MODEL NUMBER> <LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>820-3437</LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>-B no power
threads.message:
HI,

I have an <MACBOOK MODEL NUMBER>A1466</MACBOOK MODEL NUMBER> <LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>820-3437</LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>-B with no power. It had liquid contact (a bit of coffee, not much), and i replaced the <CHIP>U1959</CHIP>, <CAPACITOR>C1950</CAPACITOR> and <RESISTOR>R8167</RESISTOR> that had a bit od corrosion,  but with no sucess. It had the J6100 with a lot of corrosion, and I have taked it out.
It has green light, but no fan spin, and it consumes 95 mA on PSU.

The <SIGNAL>SYS_PWROK_R</SIGNAL> test point is missing and don't know if it is essencial  (it had corrosion and disappeared when i cleaned with IPA), and i have 0V on <SIGNAL>SYS_PWROK_R</SIGNAL>.

Can you help?

threads.title: <MACBOOK MODEL NUMBER>A1466</MACBOOK MODEL NUMBER> <LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>820-3437</LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>-B no power
threads.message:
You must check all SPI Bus Series Termination resisotrs and their traces.
Do you get any pulse on the coils?
Steady <SIGNAL>3V3_S5</SIGNAL>/SUS?

It worked. 
It seams that the <RESISTOR>R8167</RESISTOR>, besides it has the right resistance, had something wrong with it. After replacement it worked.
